<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pc.ign.com/articles/389/389931p1.html" target="top">pc.ign.com/articles/389/389931p1.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Info on combat (not as twitch-sensative as DAoC it seems) and class changing.<br>
<br>
Interesting exerpts:<br>
<br>
&quot;For instance, let's say you're facing a monster that can use Flurry of Blows. By selecting this ability, the monster can deal 25% more damage during its next attack. The game will alert you when a monster is about to use a special ability and allow you to select one or more special abilities of your own to either defend against or take advantage of a given monster's attack. In the case of Flurry of Blows, you may find yourself picking Cleave, which lets you deal 100% extra damage to an opponent using Flurry of Blows. Or you may choose to use Super Dodge which reduces the amount of damage you take from any attack. &quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Each of these abilities recycle and can be reused once they recharge. Most of them become available again within 45 seconds of being used. Some are shorter, requiring only 30 seconds to recharge, while others can require a full day or two of real time. Some, like the Super Blizzard, have such an awesome effect that they don't become available again until a week after they've been used.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Real-Time based abilities?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Now that's interesting.  A large part of me thinks that's pretty dang cool <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Of course, if you set it off by accident, it could lead to a few curse-words, lol.  But it's a cool way to give way-cool abilities but not let them become too overpowering.<br>
<br>
&quot;At a high enough level warriors and healers can opt to shift to the hybrid paladin class. Each class loses some of its abilities in order to gain those of the other class. Fighters who become paladins lose Flurry of Blows but can now Lay On Hands.&quot;<br>
<br>
I wonder what type of LoH...the EQish or D&amp;Dish LoH...<br>
<br>
&quot;All this stuff can be posted to a public global sellers' board. The item resides in escrow essentially until a buyer decides to pay the item's cost in gold (or until the seller takes it down). These transactions can even occur while the selling party is offline. Log back on, and viola! You've got a little extra cash in your bank account. You can even set up large transactions or post from a stock that players can purchase piecemeal. Make ten adamantium longswords, say, and post them for 600 gold each. Players buy as many as they want and you get the cash. There's also a global buyers' board where adventurers can post requests and buying prices for particular items. <br>
<br>
This system seemed a bit impersonal to me until the team explained the justification. &quot;We don't want you standing in town shouting, 'I need new armor. I need new armor. I need new armor,'&quot; says the other Steve. And even through the relatively faceless buyer and seller boards, you'll likely find that you're purchasing items from or selling to a relatively small community. You can pull up info on the buyers or sellers who you deal with the most and even send them private commissions. The Steves explain they're &quot;using it as a type of matchmaking service so you guys can move in to a more personal kind of transaction&quot; which includes face-to-face bartering. (A bit of this is still subject to change according to beta feedback.) &quot;<br>
<br>
I kinda miss the Britania Bizarre from UO (though I don't miss ECmart from EQ) and shopping at different vendors all over -- kind of a nice way to spend an evening in UO was shopping for crap <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  Still, I guess it has it's advantages, namely that you don't *have* to own a house to sell something (a la UO).<br>
<br>
